  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite being published in 2011, \"Virtues for the People\" has garnered attention in the academic community, evidenced by its 33 citations. However, it has yet to establish a significant presence in public or social media discourse.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Virtues for the People,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2011, has had a measured impact within scholarly environments, as reflected by its citation count of 33. This indicates that the work has been recognized by peers in the field, showcasing its contribution to ongoing academic discussions. The relatively stable citations suggest that it addresses themes relevant to the discourse surrounding virtues and public engagement.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">However, the work has not achieved significant visibility on platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, or Bluesky, indicating that it has yet to spark significant public or societal dialogue outside of academia. The absence of community interactions on these platforms underscores a potential area for increased outreach and engagement, which could enhance its societal relevance.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of commercial linkage, \"Virtues for the People\" maintains a notable presence on retail platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads. This commercial visibility reflects ongoing interest, albeit primarily from a consumer perspective rather than that of an academic or scholarly discourse, thereby suggesting that the work might appeal to a wider audience while needing to deepen its impact within scholarly circles.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, while the work demonstrates a solid scholarly uptake indicated by its citation count, the lack of broader discourse signifies a gap in its outreach efforts. Efforts to bridge this gap may enhance the impact of \"Virtues for the People\" and foster a more robust dialogue between the academic and the general community.</p>",
